entry.title: Winter Weather Advisory issued February 14 at 3:15AM CST until February 15 at 6:00AM CST by NWS La Crosse WI
entry.summary:
...Accumulating Snow Tonight...
.A quick-hitting band of snow moves through the region tonight and exits before sunrise on Thursday. Widespread snow accumulations of 1 to 2 inches are expected with two embedded corridors of higher snow totals where amounts could push 3 to 4 inches. The northern corridor is expected to run from roughly Mankato, MN northeast to near Wausau, WI while the second band develops along or just south of Interstate 90 in far southeast Minnesota and southwest Wisconsin. However, there is uncertainty in where these two bands exactly set up, which will impact forecast snow amounts. This snow could lead to slippery travel overnight and possibly for the Thursday morning commute on any untreated roads.
* WHAT...Snow expected. Total snow accumulations of 2 to 4 inches. The snow may come down at rates of over 1 inch per hour for short periods of time.
* WHERE...Portions of southeast Minnesota and central, north central and west central Wisconsin.
* WHEN...From 9 PM this evening to 6 AM CST Thursday.
* IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions.

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued February 13 at 3:19PM AKST by NWS Fairbanks AK
entry.summary:
Strong southerly chinook winds blowing across the Alaska Range will continue into Wednesday and possibly into Thursday. Temperatures this morning have risen into the 30s this morning along many highways across Interior Alaska, with some lower 40s occuring south of Fairbanks. These warm temperatures will cause walking and driving surfaces to become slippery. Some valley locations north and east of Fairbanks will remain below freezing.
Temperatures will remain very warm along the Alaska Range through Thursday and partial melting of snow and ice may occur, making travel surfaces more slippery.
Areas further north such as near Fairbanks will likely have hill top temperatures remain near freezing the next several days, while valleys will have temperatures fluctuate from near freezing during the day and back into the teens or single digits at night. This will cause travel surfaces in hills to become more slippery over the next several days as snow and ice starts to melt. Valley locations could get more slippery as well.
